Subject: netvsc: unshare skb in VF rx handler
Reply-To: joseph.salisbury@microsoft.com

The netvsc VF skb handler should make sure that skb is not
shared. Similar logic already exists in bonding and team device
drivers.

This is not an issue in practice because the VF devicex
does not send up shared skb's. But the netvsc driver
should do the right thing if it did.

Fixes: 0c195567a8f6 ("netvsc: transparent VF management")
Signed-off-by: Stephen Hemminger <sthemmin@microsoft.com>
Signed-off-by: David S. Miller <davem@davemloft.net>
(cherry picked from commit 996ed04741467f6d1552440c92988b132a9487ec)
Signed-off-by: Joseph Salisbury <joseph.salisbury@microsoft.com>
---
 drivers/net/hyperv/netvsc_drv.c | 6 ++++++
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/net/hyperv/netvsc_drv.c b/drivers/net/hyperv/netvsc_drv.c
index 9aef11ff54cc..f66e55067a1d 100644
--- a/drivers/net/hyperv/netvsc_drv.c
+++ b/drivers/net/hyperv/netvsc_drv.c
@@ -2034,6 +2034,12 @@ static rx_handler_result_t netvsc_vf_handle_frame(struct sk_buff **pskb)
 	struct netvsc_vf_pcpu_stats *pcpu_stats
 		 = this_cpu_ptr(ndev_ctx->vf_stats);
 
+	skb = skb_share_check(skb, GFP_ATOMIC);
+	if (unlikely(!skb))
+		return RX_HANDLER_CONSUMED;
+
+	*pskb = skb;
+
 	skb->dev = ndev;
 
 	u64_stats_update_begin(&pcpu_stats->syncp);
